console.log(b); // ReferenceError âŒ

ðŸ”¹ Hoisting
Q: What is hoisting in JavaScript?
Hoisting is JavaScriptâ€™s behavior of moving variable and function declarations to the top of their scope before execution.
var â†’ hoisted & initialized as undefined.
let & const â†’ hoisted but not initialized (temporal dead zone).
ðŸ‘‰ Example:
console.log(x); // undefined (var hoisted)
var x = 5;

console.log(y); // ReferenceError (TDZ)
let y = 10;

ðŸ”¹ Difference between var, let, and const
